      <bioghist id="aspace_715e57e3b3cdcd6c6a99320699dd579f">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The D.C. Rape Crisis Center was founded in 1972 as one of the first rape crisis centers in the country, and the only center at the time run primarily by and for women of color. The center provides a range of resources for survivors, both in person and through a volunteer-run hotline, including counseling, information on their rights and health, and advice for speaking to the police and making a case. The center also provides education on rape and rape prevention (including self-defense classes) to the community at large. No legislation existed at the time of the center's founding to protect or defend rape survivors, so a large portion of their work focused on political lobbying and grassroots activism. Their mission statement today describes them as, "committed to the health and wellness of people with layered identities and complex needs," as they, "work to inform, equip and engage stakeholders in eradicating sexual violence. In our 43rd year, we are working to power a culture of consent and leading the world in insistently imagining a world without rape."</p>
         <p>See their website here: http://dcrcc.org/</p>
         <p>The Feminist Alliance Against Rape (FAAR) was formed as a sub-group of the DC Rape Crisis Center in 1974 as a way to network among feminists in the anti-rape movement. FAAR published a monthly newsletter that invited others to join the discussion on violence against women and provided resources and practical information for grassroots organizers. Later, FAAR combined efforts with the National Coalition Network for the Elimination of Violence Against Women (NCN) in Wisconsin and the Alliance Against Sexual Coercion (AASC) in Boston to publish <title>Aegis: Magazine on Ending Violence Against Women,</title> which ran until 1977.</p>  
      </bioghist>
